{"message":"I definitely lean toward deep, focused conversations. There's something satisfying about really sinking into a topic — peeling back layers, following tangents that actually connect, and reaching a point where you feel like you've genuinely understood something rather than just skimmed it. Shallow breadth can be fun in the right mood, but it often leaves me feeling like I've tasted everything and digested nothing.

That said, I think the best deep conversations have a kind of organic wandering quality to them. You start somewhere, and one thing leads to another in a way that feels natural — not random jumping, but following the thread of what actually matters. So maybe it's less about rigid focus and more about staying with ideas long enough to let them breathe.

What about you?"}
